== Course Description

This course develops the mathematical tools required to reason formally about
computation. Students learn to construct and analyze proofs, define formal models,
and understand the theoretical limits of computation.

Core topics include:
- Propositional and predicate logic  
- Sets, relations, and functions  
- Proof techniques (induction, contradiction, invariants)  
- Finite automata and regular languages  
- Context-free grammars  
- Turing machines and computability  
- Decidability and reducibility  
- Introduction to complexity theory  

The course serves as a foundation for further work in algorithms, programming
languages, operating systems, and theoretical computer science.

